[normal] 3. [bold]What should [bold]the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Public service broadcasting refers to TV programmes that are broadcast for the public benefit rather than for purely commercial purposes.
[normal] (Ofcom)
[normal]The BBC’s founders believed that broadcasting could make the world a better place. Public intervention would ensure that its astonishing creative power– to enrich individuals with
[normal] knowledge, culture and information about their world, to build more cohesive communities, to engage the people of the UK and the 
[normal]whole globe in a new conversation about who we are and where we are going – would be put to work to the sole benefit of the pu
[normal]blic.
[normal]4. [bold]How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In 
[normal]developing (and reviewing) the purpose remit for bringing the UK to the world and the
[normal] 
[normal]world to the UK, the Trust must, amongst other things, seek to ensure that the BBC—
[normal]makes people in the UK aware of international issues and of the different cultures[bold] [bold]and [bold]viewpoints of people living outside the UK through news and current affairs and[bold] [bold]other outputs such as drama, comedy, documentaries, educational output and sports[bold] [bold]coverage; [bold]and
[normal] 
[normal]brings high-quality international news coverage to international audiences.
[normal] 
[normal]5.  [bold]Are the public purposes in the current Charter the[bold] right ones? How might they change?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6.  [bold]What scope, scale and remit should the BBC have? [bold]7.[bold]   [bold]Should the BBC’s output and [bold]services be provided to any greater or lesser[bold] [bold]degree for particular audiences? [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]‘politicians and the public decided very early on that broadcasting should be plac
[normal]ed in the public sphere of our national life. They believed that everyone has a right to high quality broadcast services, regardless of income, age, sex, race, religion or where they live. This is why the BBC was founded according to three public principle
[normal]s which are common to many other staples of the nation’s public life – the UK’s public health and education systems, our public parks, our museums and libraries
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]8.  [bold]What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally a[bold]nd leaves entirely to others to create?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]9.   [bold]How have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for [bold]licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?[bold]10.  [bold]What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?[bold]Paying for vulnerable users to switch to digital TV appears to us to be the responsibility of government rather than the BBC. It is part of the nation’s social and cultural policy rather than a responsibility of a single broadcaster. 
[normal]Not only will other b
[normal]roadcasters, including those with very limited public service obligations, benefit from such schemes; but it will also mean diverting licence fee income, contributed by citizens to run the BBC, rather than using general taxation, which is paid in order to 
[normal]support, among other things, infrastructure development and social welfare.
